Assignment 9: Twitter US Airline Sentiment (NLP)¶

Twitter possesses 330 million monthly active users, which allows businesses to reach a broad population and connect with customers without intermediaries. On the other hand, theres so much information that its difficult for brands to quickly detect negative social mentions that could harm their business. That's why sentiment analysis/classification, which involves monitoring emotions in conversations on social media platforms, has become a key strategy in social media marketing. Listening to how customers feel about the product/service on Twitter allows companies to understand their audience, keep on top of whats being said about their brand and their competitors, and discover new trends in the industry.

'''
Input:
Pandas DataFrame

Output:
Displays DataFrame structure 
(columns, nulls and non nulls counts and percentage highlighing columns with most number of nulls)

Retunrs:
N/A
'''
def info(dataFrame):
    print(f"{dataFrame.shape[0]} Rows x {dataFrame.shape[1]} Columns")
    missing_values             = dataFrame.isna().sum()         # Get a series counting number of empty values for each column
    non_missing_values         = dataFrame.notnull().sum()      # Get a series counting number of non empty valuesfor each column 
    missing_values_percentage  = ((missing_values * 100)/(missing_values + non_missing_values)).astype(float)
    column_datatypes           = dataFrame.dtypes               # Get a series containing data types for each column 
    
    features      = [missing_values, missing_values_percentage, column_datatypes]
    feature_names = ["No. Of Missing Values", "Missing Values %", "Data Type"]
    
    df = pd.concat(
        objs = features,
        axis = 1,
        keys = feature_names, 
        sort = True)
    
    cm = sns.light_palette("red", as_cmap=True)
    display(df.style.background_gradient(cmap=cm, subset=pd.IndexSlice[:, feature_names[1]]).format(formatter={(feature_names[1]): "{:.2f}%"}))

1.1. Drop Columns with Highest Missing Values and Low Value¶

  • airline_sentiment_confidence: We do not need this for analysis since we are goin to build our own.

  • airline_sentiment_gold: Has 99% missing values, we can drop this.

  • name: its hard to deduce sentiment based on who said the words. We might be able to find data that shows that a particular person only posts negative/sarcastic comments but also trying to detect sarcasm is out of the scope of the assignment and for the purpose of this assignment we will only focus on positive and negative sentiments based on words and not who said it so will drop this columnt too.

  • negativereason: this column only shows up when the review was negative, we could do one-hot encoding for this but it would increase the dimensionality of our model and we can get this information from the airline_sentiment column

  • for similar reasons as in above we will leave out columns with more missing values and that add less value in helping us classifying intent. We will keep a 'airline', 'retweet_count', for analysis and 'text', 'airline_sentiment' building out model

def ExploreDataDistributionByColumn(df, category):
    col_name = category

    airline_names             = df[col_name].unique()
    airline_names_count       = []
    airline_names_count_perc  = []
    ids                       = []

    count = 0
    for airline_name in  airline_names:
        total_count = df[col_name].count()
        airline_name_count = df[df[col_name] == airline_name][col_name].count()
        airline_names_count.append(airline_name_count)
        airline_names_count_perc.append(f"{str(round((airline_name_count/total_count) * 100, 2))}%")
        ids.append(count)
        count = count + 1

    return pd.DataFrame({
      "id"                : ids,
      f"{category} Name"  : airline_names,
      "Count"             : airline_names_count,
      "Category %"        : airline_names_count_perc
    })

'''
Description:
Displays a grid catplots

Input:
A list of column names
'''
def DisplayCountPlotGrid(feature, hue_col, color_palette, df):
    hues = df[hue_col].unique().tolist()
    col_index = 0
    for r in range(0, int(len(hues)), 2):
        fig, axs = plt.subplots(
            nrows=1,                                                                # Number of rows of the grid
            ncols=2,                                                                # Number of columns of the grid.
            figsize=(15,6),
            constrained_layout=True)

        for index in range(0, 2):
            if col_index < int(len(hues)):
                hue = hues[col_index]
                ax = axs.flat[index]
                df_temp = df[df[hue_col] == hue]
                ax = sns.countplot(
                    data    = df_temp,
                    x       = df_temp[feature],
                    palette = color_palette,
                    ax      = ax)
                ax.set_xlabel(feature)                                           
                ax.set_title(hue, fontsize=14)

                total = 0
                for p in ax.patches:
                    if p.get_height() > 0:
                        total += p.get_height()

                for p in ax.patches:
                    if p.get_height() > 0:
                        percentage = str(((p.get_height() / total) * 100).round(1))+ '%'
                        txt_x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()/8
                        txt_y = p.get_height() - p.get_height()/2
                        ax.text(txt_x,txt_y, percentage, color="white", weight="bold")
                     
                if int(len(ax.get_xticklabels())) > 14: 
                    ax.set_xticklabels([], rotation=45, ha='right')
                else:
                    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha='right')
            
            col_index += 1

def GetRetweetStats(df, stat):
    sentiments = df['airline_sentiment'].unique().tolist()
    stats_dfs = []
    for sentiment in sentiments:
        df_copy = df[df['airline_sentiment'] == sentiment]
        airlines = df_copy['airline'].unique().tolist()
        for airline in airlines:
            airline_stats_df = df_copy[df_copy['airline'] == airline].describe().T[[stat]]
            airline_stats_df['sentiment'] = sentiment
            airline_stats_df['airline'] = airline
            stats_dfs.append(airline_stats_df)
    return pd.concat(stats_dfs, axis=0)

#remove the html tags
def strip_mentiontags(text):
    return " ".join(filter(lambda x:x[0]!='@', text.split()))

#expand the contractions
def replace_contractions(text):
    """Replace contractions in string of text"""
    return contractions.fix(text)

#remove the numericals present in the text
def remove_numbers(text):
    text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)
    return text

def clean_text(text):
    text = strip_mentiontags(text)
    text = replace_contractions(text)
    text = remove_numbers(text)
    return text

main_data[TARGET_FEATURE] = main_data[TARGET_FEATURE].apply(lambda x: clean_text(x))

#remove the non-ASCII characters
def remove_non_ascii(words):
    """Remove non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

# convert all characters to lowercase
def to_lowercase(words):
    """Convert all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

# Remove the punctuations
def remove_punctuation(words):
    """Remove punctuation from list of tokenized words"""
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
        if new_word != '':
            new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

# Remove the stop words
def remove_stopwords(words):
    """Remove stop words from list of tokenized words"""
    stopwords_local = list(set(stopwords)-set(stop_words_common))
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords_local:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

# lemmatize the words
def lemmatize_list(text):
    words = ' '.join(text)
    text = nlp(words)
    words = [word.lemma_ if word.lemma_ != '-PRON-' else word.text for word in text]
    return words

def normalize(words):
    words = remove_non_ascii(words)
    words = to_lowercase(words)
    words = remove_punctuation(words)
    words = remove_stopwords(words)
    words = lemmatize_list(words)
    return ' '.join(words)

def PlotWordCloud(df, sentiment):
    sentiment_data = df[df['airline_sentiment'] == sentiment]
    words = ' '.join(sentiment_data['text'])
    cleaned_word = " ".join([word for word in words.split()])
    wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=STOPWORDS,
                          background_color='black',
                          width=2500,
                          height=2500
                         ).generate(cleaned_word)
    plt.figure(1,figsize=(12, 12))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(
        f"[Sentiment={sentiment}]",
        fontdict={
            'fontsize': "xx-large",
            'fontweight' : "bold"})
    plt.show()

def GetCountVectFeaturesModelData(df):
    vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_features=2000)                # Keep only 500 features as number of features will increase the processing time.
    data_features = vectorizer.fit_transform(df['text'])
    data_features = data_features.toarray()
    
    X = data_features
    y = df.airline_sentiment
    
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)
    
    print("==========GetCountVectFeaturesModelData==============")
    print(f"x_train: {x_train.shape}")
    print(f"y_train: {y_train.shape}\n")
    
    return {
        "x_train"   : x_train,
        "y_train"   : y_train,
        "x_test"    : x_test,
        "y_test"    : y_test,

def GetTfidfVectorizedModelData(df):    
    vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=2000)
    data_features = vectorizer.fit_transform(df['text'])
    data_features = data_features.toarray()

    X = data_features
    y = df.airline_sentiment
    
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=1)
    
    print("==========GetTfidfVectorizedModelData==============")
    print(f"x_train: {x_train.shape}")
    print(f"y_train: {y_train.shape}\n")
    
    return {
        "x_train"    : x_train,
        "y_train"    : y_train,
        "x_test"     : x_test,
        "y_test"     : y_test,
        "vectorizer" : vectorizer
    }

def GetOptimalLearners(model_data, vectoriser_name):
    # Finding optimal number of base learners using k-fold CV ->
    base_ln = np.arange(1,20,1).tolist()

    # K-Fold Cross - validation .
    cv_scores = []
    for b in base_ln:
        clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = b)
        scores = cross_val_score(clf, model_data['x_train'], model_data['y_train'], cv = 5, scoring = 'accuracy')
        cv_scores.append(scores.mean())
        
    # plotting the error as k increases
    error = [1 - x for x in cv_scores]                                 #error corresponds to each nu of estimator
    optimal_learners = base_ln[error.index(min(error))]                #Selection of optimal nu of n_estimator corresponds to minimum error.
    plt.plot(base_ln, error)                                           #Plot between each nu of estimator and misclassification error
    xy = (optimal_learners, min(error))
    plt.annotate('(%s, %s)' % xy, xy = xy, textcoords='data')
    plt.xlabel("Number of base learners")
    plt.title(f"{vectoriser_name}")
    plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
    plt.show()
    return optimal_learners

  • TF-IDF Vectoriser : Select n_estimators = 19

def DisplayConfusionMatrix(model, model_data, model_name):
    y_predict = model.predict(model_data['x_test'])
    confusion_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(model_data['y_test'], y_predict, labels=[0, 1, 2])
    confusion_matix_df = pd.DataFrame(
        confusion_matrix,
        index   = [i for i in ["Actual Neutral", "Actual Negative", "Actual Positive"]],
        columns = [i for i in ["Predicted Neutral", "Predicted Negative", "Predicted Positive"]])
    
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in confusion_matrix.flatten()]
    group_percetages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in confusion_matrix.flatten()/np.sum(confusion_matrix)]
    
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in zip(group_counts, group_percetages)]
    labels = np.array(labels).reshape(3, 3)
    plt.figure(figsize= (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matix_df, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel("True Label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted Label")
    plt.title(model_name)
    
def ConfusionMatrixBulkPlot(models, data):
    for clf_model_name in models:
        clf_model = models[clf_model_name]
        DisplayConfusionMatrix(model=clf_model, model_data=data, model_name = clf_model_name)
    
'''
Description:
Given the model, computes models perfomance on test and training data.
Perf metrics displayed are: Accuracy, Recall, F1 Score, and precision.

Input:
model - The learning model.

Returns:
A dictionary containing models perfomace.
'''
def GetMetricsScore(model, model_data):
    
    pred_train = model.predict(model_data['x_train'])
    pred_test  = model.predict(model_data['x_test'])

    train_accuracy = model.score(model_data['x_train'], model_data['y_train'])
    test_accuracy  = model.score(model_data['x_test'], model_data['y_test'])

    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(model_data['y_train'], pred_train, pos_label='positive', average='micro')
    test_recall  = metrics.recall_score(model_data['y_test'], pred_test, pos_label='positive', average='micro')

    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(model_data['y_train'], pred_train, pos_label='positive', average='micro')
    test_precision  = metrics.precision_score(model_data['y_test'], pred_test, pos_label='positive', average='micro')

    f1_score_train = 2 * ((train_precision * train_recall)/(train_precision + train_recall))
    f1_score_test = 2 * ((test_precision * test_recall)/(test_precision + test_recall))
    
    return {
        'Accuracy_Test'   : test_accuracy,
        'Accuracy_Train'  : train_accuracy,
        'Recall_Test'     : test_recall,
        'Recall_Train'    : train_recall,
        'Precision_Test'  : test_precision,
        'Precision_Train' : train_precision,
        'F1_Score_Train'  : f1_score_train,
        'F1_Score_Test'   : f1_score_test
    }

def GetModelsScoreDataFrame(models, model_data):
    scores = None
    for model_name in models:
        scores = GetMetricsScore(models[model_name], model_data)
        print(f"{model_name}")
    scores_overview_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=scores.keys())

    for model_name in models:
        scores = GetMetricsScore(models[model_name], model_data)
        scores_overview_df.loc[model_name] = scores

    return scores_overview_df

def Top40WordsCloud(models, vectorisor):
    for model_name in models:
        model = models[model_name]
        all_features = vectorisor.get_feature_names()              #Instantiate the feature from the vectorizer
        top_features=''                                            # Addition of top 40 feature into top_feature after training the model
        feat=model.feature_importances_
        features=np.argsort(feat)[::-1]
        for i in features[0:40]:
            top_features+=all_features[i]
            top_features+=', '

        print(" ") 

        wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color="white",colormap='viridis',width=2000, 
                                  height=2000).generate(top_features)

        # Display the generated image:
        plt.figure(1,figsize=(12, 12))
        plt.imshow(wordcloud)
        plt.title(f'[{model_name}: Top 40 features WordCloud]', fontsize=25)
        plt.axis("off")
        plt.show()

def BuildAndGetModel(model_data_x, model_data_y):
    rf_estimator=RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1)
    rf_estimator.fit(model_data_x, model_data_y)
    pprint.pprint(rf_estimator)

    parameters = {
        'max_features'      : [2, 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 50, 100],
        "n_estimators"      : [19, 15]
    }

    acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)
    scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)
    grid_obj = RandomizedSearchCV(
        estimator=rf_estimator,
        param_distributions=parameters,
        n_jobs=-1,
        n_iter=20,
        scoring=scorer,
        cv=5,
        random_state=1,
    )
    
    gird_obj = grid_obj.fit(model_data_x,model_data_y)
    rf_estimator = grid_obj.best_estimator_
    return rf_estimator

def GetCrossValidatedModels(model_data_dic, vectoriser):
    # Undersampled Model Data
    rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=1)
    x_train_un, y_train_un = rus.fit_resample(model_data_dic['x_train'], model_data_dic['y_train'])

    # Oversampled Model Data
    sm = SMOTE(k_neighbors=15, random_state=1)
    x_train_over, y_train_over = sm.fit_resample(model_data_dic['x_train'], model_data_dic['y_train'])
    
    undersampled_clf = BuildAndGetModel(x_train_un, y_train_un)
    oversmpled_clf   = BuildAndGetModel(x_train_over, y_train_over)
    base_clf         = BuildAndGetModel(model_data_dic['x_train'], model_data_dic['y_train'])    
    
    return {
        f'{vectoriser} with Oversampled Data' : undersampled_clf,
        f'{vectoriser} with Undersampled Data': oversmpled_clf,
        f'{vectoriser} with Normal Data'      : base_clf,
    }

5. Conlusions¶

  • Both Models perform relatively well regarddless of the type of vectorisation used.
  • More positive words showing up in top features,this could be because the data has more positive intents than it has negative intents.
  • We have normal data 75% in test and 99% training, the model is overfit to the training data.
  • United has the highest number of negative retweets
  • Delta seems to have consistnt high engagement regardless of the sentiment of the tweet.
  • SouthWest Sees a high number of positive engagments with 8.2% in positive sentiment retweets compaired to 3.8 and 3.9 of neutral and negative sentimnts retweets respectively.
  • For Virgin America, the most occurring problem is customer service and flight booking problems
  • For united, similarly to Virgin America, customer service and late flight.

  • For all flights we see late flight and customer service as the most common and prevaling issue.

  • We see most of the issues customers had were from customer service and late flight.

  • Late Flight and bad flight seem fall under the same category. Its not clear what counts as bad flight.

  • The airline data is almost evenly distributed. only Virgin America seems to be an outlier with 3.44%. 60%+ of the data contains negative seniments with 21%+ nuetral and only 16% positive. The data is imbalanced and skewed toward the the negative sentiments and this might affect our model.

  • We might need to generate some data for positive sentiments and neutral sentiments to help the model generalise better. airline_sentiment_confidence: We do not need this for analysis since we are goin to build our own.

  • airline_sentiment_gold: Has 99% missing values, we can drop this.

  • name: its hard to deduce sentiment based on who said the words. We might be able to find data that shows that a particular person only posts negative/sarcastic comments but also trying to detect sarcasm is out of the scope of the assignment and for the purpose of this assignment we will only focus on positive and negative sentiments based on words and not who said it so will drop this columnt too.

  • negativereason: this column only shows up when the review was negative, we could do one-hot encoding for this but it would increase the dimensionality of our model and we can get this information from the airline_sentiment column

  • for similar reasons as in above we will leave out columns with more missing values and that add less value in helping us classifying intent. We will keep a 'airline', 'retweet_count', for analysis and 'text', 'airline_sentiment' building out model
